<section xml:id="s_groups" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Groups</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            This first quarter of Math 331 is devoted entirely to the study of groups. This a fitting place to begin both as groups represent a type of algebraic object with near minimal structure and are omnipresent in the world of mathematics and the empirical sciences more generally. More conceptually, groups are intimately connected with the notion of symmetry in mathematics. Put plainly, wherever you find mathematical discussion of symmetry, a group usually lurks in the background as the thing that defines that symmetry. We will see plenty of examples of this in the coming days. In the meantime, for an excellent elaboration of this theme, check out Keith Conrad's blurb <url href="https://kconrad.math.uconn.edu/blurbs/grouptheory/whygroups.pdf"><em>Why groups?</em></url>
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_def_group">
    <title>Definition</title>
    <definition xml:id="d_group">
    <title>Groups</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    A group is an ordered pair <m>(G,\cdot)</m> where <m>G</m> is a nonempty set and <m>\cdot</m> is a binary operation
    <md>
        <mrow>G\times G \amp \xrightarrow{\phantom{XX}\bullet\phantom{XX}} G</mrow>
        <mrow>(g,h) \amp \longmapsto g\cdot h</mrow>
    </md>,
    satisfying the following axioms. 
    <ol marker="(i)">
        <li>
            <title>Associativity</title>
            <p>
                For all <m>g_1,g_2,g_3\in G</m> we have 
                <men xml:id="eq_assoc">
                    (g_1\cdot g_2)\cdot g_3 = g_1\cdot (g_2\cdot g_3)
                </men>.                
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Group identity</title>
            <p>
                There is an element <m>e\in G</m>, such that for all <m>g\in G</m>, we have 
                <men xml:id="eq_id">
                    g\cdot e = e\cdot g = g
                </men>.
                We call <m>e</m> the <term>group identity</term> of <m>G</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <title>Group inverses</title>
            <p>
                For all <m>g\in G</m> there is an element <m>g^{-1}\in G</m> satisfying
                <men xml:id="eq_inv">
                    g\cdot g^{-1} = g^{-1}\cdot g = e
                </men>.
                We call <m>g^{-1}</m> the <term>group inverse</term> of <m>g</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <assumption xml:id="fiat_group_law">
        <title>Group law notation</title>
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                You are free to denote the binary group law in any manner you like. Often, as in <xref first="spec_ring_additive_groups" last="spec_ring_mult_groups"/>, we will make a notational choice that reflects the specific nature of a given group.  
            </p>
            <p>
                Furthermore, with the exception of the case where <m>+</m> is used to denote the group law, we will often omit the group operation symbol when writing expressions involving group elements.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </assumption>
    <activity xml:id="spec_ring_additive_groups">
        <title>Ring additive groups</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>R\in \{\Z,\Q, \R, \C\}</m>, and let <m>+</m> be the usual addition operation on <m>R</m>. The pair <m>(R,+)</m> is a group, called the <term>additive group</term> of <m>R</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                The group identity of <m>R</m> is <m>0</m>, also known as the <em>additive identity</em> of <m>R</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Given any <m>r\in R</m>, its group inverse is its minus, <m>-r</m>, also known as the <em>additive inverse</em> <m>r</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <activity xml:id="spec_ring_mult_groups">
        <title>Ring multiplicative groups</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>R\in \{\Z,\Q, \R, \C\}</m>. An element <m>r\in R</m> is a <term>unit</term> (or <term>(multiplicatively) invertible</term> if there is an element <m>r^{-1}\in R</m> satisfying <m>r\,r^{-1}=r^{-1}\, r=1</m>. In this case <m>r^{-1}</m> is called the <term>multiplicative inverse</term> of <m>r</m>. Define <m>R^*</m> to be the set of all units of <m>R</m>: <ie/>, 
                <me>
                    R^* = \{ r\in R \mid \text{there exists } r^{-1}\in R \text{ such that } r\, r^{-1}=r^{-1}\, r = 1 \}
                </me>.
                If <m>R\in \{\Q, \R, \C\}</m>, then <m>R^*=R-\{0\}</m>, since in these number systems all nonzero elements have a multiplicative inverse. By contrast, we have
                <me>
                    Z^*=\{1, -1\}
                </me>,
                since <m>1</m> and <m>-1</m> are the only integers that have an integer multiplicative inverse. 
            </p>
            <p>
               The <m>(R^*,\cdot)</m>, where <m>\cdot</m> is the usual multiplciation operation on <m>R</m>, is a group called the <term>multiplicative group</term> of <m>R</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                The group identity of <m>R^*</m> is <m>1</m>, also known as the <em>multiplicative identity</em> of <m>R</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                Given any <m>r\in R^*</m>, its group inverse is the multiplicative inverse <m>r^{-1}</m> defined above. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <definition xml:id="d_abelian_group">
    <title>Abelian group</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
        A group <m>(G,\cdot)</m> is <term>abelian</term> (or <term>commutative</term>) if 
        <me>
            g\, h=h\, g
        </me>
        for all <m>g,h\in G</m>. The group is <term>nonabelian</term> (or <term>noncommutative</term>), if it is not abelian. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <activity xml:id="spec_gln">
        <title>General linear group</title>
        <p>
           Let <m>R\in \{\Q, \R, \C\}</m>. The set of all <m>n\times n</m> matrices with coefficients in <m>R</m> is denoted <m>\ML_n(R)</m>. We denote by <m>\GL_n(R)</m> the set of invertible <m>n\times n</m> matrices with coefficients in <m>R</m>: <ie/>, 
            <md>
                <mrow>\GL_n(R) \amp </mrow>
            </md>
           
           is denoted <m>\GL_n(R)</m>: <ie/>, 
           <md>
            <mrow>\GL_n(R)  \amp = \{A\in M_n(R)\mid A \text{ is invertible} \} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp =\{A\in M_n(R)\mid \det A\ne 0\}</mrow>
           </md>.
           The pair <m>(\GL_n(R), \cdot)</m>, where <m>\cdot</m> is the usual matrix multiplication operation, is a group called the <term>general linear group</term> of degree <m>n</m> over <m>R</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            The group identity of <m>\GL_n(R)</m> is the <m>n\times n</m> identity matrix <m>I</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Given any <m>A\in \GL_n(R)</m>, its group inverse is the matrix inverse <m>A^{-1}</m>.
        </p>
    </activity>
    <example xml:id="eg_nonabelian_gln">
    <title><m>\GL_n(R)</m> is nonabelian</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R\in \{\Q,\R, \C\}</m> and let <m>n\geq 2</m>. Prove that <m>\GL_n(R)</m> is a nonabelian group. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
    Let 
    <md>
        <mrow>A \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \amp B\amp= \\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
    </md>.
    We have <m>A, B\in \GL_2(R)</m> (easy determinant computation), and furthermore
    <md>
        <mrow>AB \amp  = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
        <mrow>BA \amp  = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
    </md>.
    Since <m>AB\ne BA</m>, we conclude that <m>\GL_2(R)</m> is nonabelian. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Next, given any <m>n\geq 3</m>, consider the block matrices 
        <md>
            <mrow>A' \amp = \begin{bmatrix}
            A\amp 0 \\
            0\amp I_{n-2}   
            \end{bmatrix} \amp B'\amp=\begin{bmatrix}
            B\amp 0 \\
            0\amp I_{n-2}   
            \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
        </md>,
        where <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are the <m>2\times 2</m> matrices above. From properties of block matrix arithmetic it follows that <m>A'</m> and <m>B'</m> are invertible (in fact, <m>\det A'=\det B'=1</m>) and 
        <md>
            <mrow>A'B' \amp = \begin{bmatrix}
            AB\amp 0 \\
            0\amp I_{n-2}   
            \end{bmatrix} \amp B'A'\amp=\begin{bmatrix}
            BA\amp 0 \\
            0\amp I_{n-2}   
            \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
        </md>.
        Since <m>AB\ne BA</m>, we conclude that <m>\GL_n(R)</m> is nonabelian, as desired. 
    </p>
    </solution>
    </example>
    
    
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_product_groups">
    <title>Product groups</title>
    <p>
        The group product operation is an easy and important manner of constructing new groups from a collection of existing ones. 
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="d_product_group">
    <title>Product group</title>
    <notation>
        <usage><m>G\times H</m></usage>
      <description>product of groups <m>G</m> and <m>H</m></description>
    </notation>
    <notation>
        <usage><m>\prod_{i\in I} G_i</m></usage>
      <description>product of family of groups <m>(G_i)_{i\in I}</m></description>
    </notation>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Given groups <m>G</m> and <m>H</m>, the <term>product group</term> <m>G\times H</m> is the group with underlying set 
    <me>
        G\times H=\{(g,h)\mid g\in G, h\in H\}
    </me>
    and group operation 
    <me>
        (g,h)\cdot (g',h')=(gg', hh')
    </me>.
    More generally, given a family of groups <m>(G_i)_{i\in I}</m> indexed by a nonempty set <m>I</m>, their product is the group <m>\prod_{i\in I}G_i</m> with underling set 
    <me>
        \prod_{i\in I}G_i=\{(g_i)_{i\in I}\mid g_i\in G_i \text{ for all } i\in I\}
    </me>
    and group operation 
    <me>
        (g_i)_{i\in I}\cdot (h_i)_{i\in I}=(g_ih_i)_{i\in I}
    </me>
    for all <m>g=(g_i)_{i\in I}</m> and <m>h=(h_i)_{i\in I}</m> in <m>\prod_{i\in I}G_i</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        We write <m>G^n</m> for the <m>n</m>-fold group product 
        <me>
            \underset{n \text{ times}}{\underbrace{G\times G\times \cdots \times G}}
        </me>
        of a group <m>G</m> with itself.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
    <title>Arbitrary products</title>
    <p>
    See <xref ref="ss_tuples_cart_prod" text="title"/> for more details about tuples and Cartesian products indexed by arbitrary sets <m>I</m>. 
    </p>
    </remark>
    
    <proposition xml:id="prop_product_group">
        <title>Product group</title>
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                Given a family <m>(G_i)_{i\in I}</m> of groups indexed by a nonempty set <m>I</m>, the product <m>\prod_{i\in I} G_i</m> is a group with respect to the binary operation defined in <xref ref="d_product_group"/>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                We verify each group axiom in turn. 
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Given elements <m>g=(g_i)_{i\in I}</m>, <m>h=(h_i)_{i\in I}</m>, and <m>k=(k_i)_{i\in I}</m> of <m>\prod_{i\in I} G_i</m>, we have 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>g(hk) \amp = (g_i)_{i\in I} \cdot \left( (h_i)_{i\in I}\cdot (k_i)_{i\in I}\right)</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (g_i)_{i\in I} \cdot (h_i k_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (g_i (h_ik_i))_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = ((g_ih_i)k_i)_{i\in I} \amp (\text{assoc. of } G_i)</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (g_ih_i)_{i\in I}\cdot (k_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \left((g_i)_{i\in I}\cdot (h_i)_{i\in I}\right)\cdot (k_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp =(gh)k</mrow>
                            </md>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>e_i</m> denote the identity element of <m>G_i</m> for each <m>i\in I</m>, and let <m>e=(e_i)_{i\in I}</m>. For any <m>g=(g_i)_{i\in I}</m>, we have 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>g\cdot e \amp = (g_i)_{i\in I} \cdot (e_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (g_ie_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (g_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = g</mrow>
                            </md>
                            and 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>e\cdot g \amp = (e_i)_{i\in I} \cdot (g_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (e_ig_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (g_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = g</mrow>
                            </md>,
                            showing that <m>e=(e_i)_{i\in I}</m> satisfies the group identity axiom. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Given <m>g=(g_i)_{i\in I}\in \prod_{i\in I}G_i</m>, let <m>g^{-1}=(g_i^{-1})_{i\in I}</m>. We have 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>g\cdot g^{-1} \amp = (g_i)_{i\in I} \cdot (g_i^{-1})_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (g_ig_i^{-1})_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (e_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = e</mrow>
                            </md>
                            and 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>g^{-1}\cdot g \amp = (g_i^{-1})_{i\in I} \cdot (g_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (g_i^{-1}g_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = (e_i)_{i\in I}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = e</mrow>
                            </md>,
                            showing that <m>g^{-1}</m> is a group inverse of <m>g</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </proof>
    </proposition>

    
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_elem_group_proos">
    <title>Elementary properties</title>
    <proposition xml:id="th_group_props">
    <title>Group properties</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
   Let <m>(G,\cdot)</m> be a group. 
   <ol>
    <li>
        <title>Cancellation laws</title>
        <p>
            Let <m>g,h,k\in G</m>. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>gh=gk</m> if and only if <m>h=k</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>hg=kg</m> if and only if <m>h=k</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <title>Uniqueness of identity</title>
        <p>
            The identity element of <m>G</m> is unique: <ie/>, there is exactly one element <m>e\in G</m> satisfying <xref ref="eq_id"/>.     
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <title>Uniqueness of inverse</title>
        <p>
            Every <m>g\in G</m> has a unique inverse element: <ie/>, for each <m>g\in G</m> there is exactly one element <m>g^{-1}\in G</m> satisfying <xref ref="eq_inv"/>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>(g^{-1})^{-1}=g</m> for all <m>g\in G</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <title>Inverse of product</title>
        <p>
            <m>(g\, h)^{-1}=h^{-1}\, g^{-1}</m> for all <m>g,h\in G</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    
    <li>
        <title>Generalized associativity</title>
        <p>
           Any two parenthetical groupings of an <m>n</m>-tuple <m>(g_1,g_2,\dots, g_n)\in G^n</m> give rise to the same product in <m>G</m>, which we denote as 
           <me>
            g_1g_2\cdots g_n
           </me>.
           For example, we have  
           <md>
            <mrow> ((g_1\, g_2)\, g_3)\, g_4 \amp = (g_1\, (g_2\, g_3))\, g_4  </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = g_1\, ((g_2\, g_3)\, g_4)</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = g_1\, (g_2\, (g_3\, g_4))</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp =(g_1\, g_2)(g_3\, g_4)</mrow>
           </md>
           for any <m>(g_1,g_2,g_3,g_4)\in G^4</m>, and we denote this common element <m>g_1\,g_2\,g_3\,g_4</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
   </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </proposition>
    <definition xml:id="d_group_exp">
    <title>Group exponentiation</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>G</m> be a group. Given <m>n\in \Z</m> and <m>g\in G</m>, the <term><m>n</m>-th power</term> of <m>g</m>, denoted <m>g^n</m> is defined via cases as follows.
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
               <m>g^0=e</m> 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Given positive integer <m>n</m>, we define 
                <md>
                    <mrow>g^n \amp =\underset{n \text{ times}}{\underbrace{g\, g\cdots g}}\amp g^{-n} \amp=\underset{n \text{ times}}{\underbrace{g^{-1}\, g^{-1}\cdots g^{-1}}}</mrow>
                </md>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition xml:id="d_order_group_element">
        <title>Group element order</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>g</m> be an element of the group <m>G</m>. The <term>order</term> of <m>g</m>, denoted <m>\ord g</m> is defined as follows.
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If there is no positive integer <m>n</m>, such that <m>g^n=e</m>, then <m>g</m> has <term>infinite order</term>, denoted <m>\ord g=\infty</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           If there is a positive integer <m>k</m> such that <m>g^k=e</m>, then <m>\ord g</m> is defined as the smallest positive integer <m>n</m> satisfying <m>g^n=e</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>   
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="eg_order_inverse">
    <title>Order of inverse</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>g</m> be an element of the group <m>G</m>.

    Prove: <m>\ord g=\ord g^{-1}</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    
    </example>
    <example xml:id="eg_infinite_order">
    <title>Element of infinite order</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Assume <m>g</m> is an element of the group <m>G</m> of infinite order. 

    Prove that the elements <m>g^n</m>, <m>n\in \Z</m>, are all distinct. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </example>
    

    
    </subsection>
    
</section>